title: Blizzard of Customizable, Mailable Snowflake Ornaments: with Kickstarter!

description.text:
Snowflakes are unique. Now so are snowflake ornaments! So why print one ornament when you can have a Blizzard! I'm making a unique line of 2014 Kickstarter snowflakes. If you'd like to back this 3D printed art project, see https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/laird/snowburst-2014 . The project video is https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=OlOK49rwcew&feature=youtu.be . This Thing is customizable and can generate:
  • Snowball ornaments, an arrangement of three intersecting snowflakes to print and hang.
  • Snowflake ornaments, flat snowflakes to hang.
  • Snowflakes, perfect for scattering around for decoration.
    • Prints quickly and easily out of PLA, for ecologically friendly snowflake ornaments! I'm printing and mailing them to my friends and relatives for Xmas. They're specifically designed to be mailable flat, then (for the 'snowballs') assembled by the recipient. Print the snowball assembly instructions at https://docs.google.com/a/popk.in/drawings/d/1N98OkbFxATnuw_ZJArYcHN3YTW1GWePNyFZi0X45olo and send them to your recipient. The ornaments aren't going to blow off your tree. It was blowing up a storm, and as you can see http://youtu.be/EulzPW4e3Nc
    and the clips held just fine. I created these because, between the wind and the temperature, these are the only interesting snowflakes we're going to see here in Florida. UPDATED:
  • Improved rendering performance (thanks, [email protected])
  • Added "Lithophane of snowflake", which look very nice when backlit. (Removed: I'll make this a different ornament)
  • Made "hexagons" varying number of sides, giving more variety to the snowflakes.
  • Made 'hexagon' widths slightly random
  • added 'minthickness' tweak, so you can set this to ensure that all lines are thick enough to print and remove from the print bed on your printer. By default some lines can be 0.6mm, which is one extruded line. Making this 1.0 ensure that thin lines are two extruded lines, etc.
  • added another digit to the label so that you can use a date (DDMMYYYY) so you can generate birthday snowflakes.
  • Assembly instructions: https://docs.google.com/a/popk.in/drawings/d/1N98OkbFxATnuw_ZJArYcHN3YTW1GWePNyFZi0X45olo .
  • Added "Snowflake Ornament" part, which has a hook and snowflake number
  • Made inner hexagon random.
To make your own snowflake, open this Thing in Customizer, and enter a few settings to make your own, only-one-in-the-world snowflake ornament.

Pick a seed number, which will generate your unique snowflake. Try entering your phone number, zip code, or birth date! Pick the part to view. These are:
  • Preview of the assembled snowflake ornament. Don't print this.
  • Plate that contains the three pieces that assemble into a snowball. Print this. Arranged to fit nicely on a Replicator print bed.
  • Snowball1, Snowball2 and Snowball3, The three parts to assemble, to print one at a time. These are useful if the plate doesn't fit on your printer.
  • Snowflake is just the snowflake to print by itself. This is a nice decoration, and prints quickly, so they make great holiday gifts!
  • "Snowflake Ornament" is a snowflake with a hook on it, for hanging.

Usually the defaults are fine. This tab lets you tweak the snowflakes if you don't like the defaults. The settings are:
  • Adjust spacing between snowflakes on build plate. Negative makes them closer, positive makes them further apart (mm). Look at the Plate and set this so that the three snowflakes are close together but not touching.
  • Trim the ends of the guides by this much (mm) if they are too long. 0 to not trim.
  • Ring radius (mm).
  • Clip thickness (mm).
  • Scale to fit on build plate, if needed. Does not scale thickness. If the ornament is too large for your build plate, make this smaller, such as 0.8. Normally leave at 1.0.
  • Clearance between the pieces. If the pieces are too hard to assemble, make this larger.
  • "min thickness" limits how thin the snowflake parts can be (mm). If you'd like the snowflake to be thicker/stronger, make this larger.
This lets you preview the print on your build plate, so you can see what fits. This doesn't affect the print, but it lets you see if you need to tweak the snowflake to fit your particular printer.

Assembly instructions for the "snowball" snowflake ornament, with diagrams, are at https://docs.google.com/a/popk.in/drawings/d/1N98OkbFxATnuw_ZJArYcHN3YTW1GWePNyFZi0X45olo .
  • Print the parts. Either print the plate (which fits nicely on a Replicator), or each of the three parts one at a time. Clean up the prints. In particular, make sure that the slots are clear so that the pieces can slide together.
  • Start with Piece 1, which is the piece one slot with a hook at one end, and the label with the snowflake number on it.
  • Slide the piece that has slots on both the top and bottom down into the first piece. You may need to twist the clip to the side to allow the second piece to slide into place.
  • Slide the third piece down over the first two. This locks them together firmly.
    • If you prefer the flat snowflake ornament, just print that part! And hang your unique new ornament!

title: ACME rod upgrade for Makerbot Cupcake

description.text: Simplest, lowest hassle Zwobble elimination that I know of for the Cupcake.

1)Print 4 ACME Nut Holders, these work with 7/8" Wrench size nuts which is typical for 1/2" ACME nuts. 2)Print 4 Z extender Bases Direct from Zydac's Z extender kit (as in NOT my design), Thisincreases the base height and reduces the length of the rod which in turn moves the worst wobble spot (the center of rod) up away from your typical printing height and reduces the max wobble (straightness is expressed in 1/1000/s per inch, so less inches gives more straightness) 3) Cut 4 9" lengths of 1/2" -20tpi Good quality ACME rod I use Bright zinc tested for straightness on a glass table. (strength is no issue here, only straightness/ thread quality) 4) Lathe down 20mm to 7.8~7.9mm to slide fit a Skate bearing on one end of each rod. (what is normally used on the cupcake for Z bearings) 5) lathe down 34mm of the other end of each rod to the same size. 6) Bolt Z Extenders to cupcake "floor" using existing hardware 7) Press fit ACME its in to holders and bolt to BOTTOM of acrylic Z platform clearancing for Rods if necessary (mine fit, but only by 1/2mm on each side. 8) OPTIONAL If your ACME nuts are tight fitting you will need to swap your stepper pulley for the smaller size used on the Cupcake X + Y stages. Calibrate your Z stage steps per MM depending on if you had to upgrade your pulley or not. I do sell the Rods pre-Turned down on Ebay and include the nuts which fit perfect for use with the stock Z pulley if you don't have access to a Lathe, and the ACME rods are available from McMasterCarr. description.text:
This is my take on the Google Cardboard idea – a frame with lenses that very inexpensively turns your phone into a pair of VR goggles, like a very low budget Oculus Rift. Google Cardboard is very bulky though, and makes it hard to use the touchscreen while the phone is inside. It's also impractical to transport. So I made this.

Features:

  • collapsible
  • collapsed only 6 mm flat
  • uses inexpensive Google Cardboard lenses (e.g. from eBay, see below)
  • attachment points for a head strap
  • compatible with Google Cardboard apps
  • display stays accessible (mostly; i wouldn't type a text on it, but selecting things works fine)

What you need to buy:

  • Lenses: Google Cardboard compatible biconvex lenses, diameter 25mm, focal length 45mm (search on e.g. eBay)
  • some M2 screws or a diameter 2mm carbon rod

Test prints were done using ABS filament. You may have to rescale when printing with PLA to account for shrinking with ABS.

description.text:
Introducing the second free design from Parallel Goods!

Our Push-Pin Clip allows you to hang things on the wall without damaging your flat stock or other art. The Push-Pin Clip is also great for hanging reminders and notes to yourself for when you're coming and going, or for creating quick collages.

The Push-Pin Clip prints fast, and the two-part design allows you to easily customize the colors to match your decor or whatever artwork you're hanging. Be sure to check out the Print Settings & Post-Printing Instructions to make sure you get the most out of the Push-Pin Clip.

The Push-Pin Clip is part of our newly released Entryway Collection, now available along with other great designs at parallelgoods.co

Follow us on Thingiverse, join our Thingiverse Group, and follow us on Twitter and Instagram @parallelgoods and stay tuned!

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Notes:

The Push-Pin Clip consists of two parts and is designed to be printed in PLA. We went through lots of experimentation and many iterations to develop Slic3r settings which balance the speed of the print with robustness. Every 3D printer is different, but these settings should give you a fine starting point for use on your own printer.

Slic3r Settings PLA

  • Layer Height: .2mm
  • Vertical Shells (Perimeters): 3
  • Horizontal Shells (Solid Layers): Top – 3, Bottom – 3
  • Infill: 100%
  • Prints WITHOUT Supports

The Push-Pin clip was designed to be printed as it is oriented in the file. You will need both parts to make one push-pin clip.

Additional hardware

As the name implies, to mount the push-pin clips, you’re going to need push-pins. While any standard push-pin will work, we recommend #4 Moore Aluminum Push-Pins, which have a 1/2” aluminum head and a 1/2” point.

Take the two printed parts and slide the straight slide of the clip into the slot of the saddle. You should feel the clip click into the saddle. Insert a push-pin through the pin hole of the saddle and press into the wall. Gently depress the clip tab and insert to hold art work in place! Enjoy!

The push-pin clip is great for photographs, flat stock posters, and art prints. Try mixing and matching filament colors for a nice effect.

title: Solidoodle 3 DTI Dial Test Indicator Clamp

description.text:
Dial test indicator clamp for the Solidoodle 3 based on previous designs but with two DTI attachment options. This stl file provides an 8mm mounting hole for the DTI in a central position between shafts and a second bracket to mount the DTI as shown in the jpg image.
I have included an igs version of the model so that it can be modified to take different DTI's and or Magnets. The magnets for this model are 10mm x 1mm. The best way to mount the magnets is to use Acetone and a clamp. Acetone is readily available through Ebay. Just drip a small amount of acetone into the magnet mount hole and locate the magnet, clamp in position and leave for about 1 hour.
Added picture of clamp in location, move clamp by hand in X direction and using motors in the Y axis.

It is specifically designed to replace the spool holder on the Vector 3 3d printer. It is fully adjustable to accept all sizes of 1kg & 500g reels.

Instructions

To make a reel roller you need to print the following:
1 x Reel Roller Fixing Plate
1 x Reel Roller Slider
1 x Reel Roller Spacer
2 x Reel Roller Inner
2 x Reel Roller Outer

Other Parts List (all available from ebay)
8 x 608 ZZ [8 x 22 x 7] Roller Skate Ball Bearings
8 x M3 x 25mm Hex Head Screws
2 x M3 x 18mm Hex Head Screws
2 x M3 x 12mm Hex Head Screws
12 x M3 Nuts
4 x M3 washers
1 x M6 x 16mm Hexagon Head Bolt
1 x M6 Butterfly Nut

  1. Lift the build plate to the top of the Z-axis to give you room to work.
  2. Insert 2 x M3 x 18mm Hex Head Screws and 1 x M6 Hexagon Head Bolt from the underside of the Fixing Plate.
  3. Add Butterfly Nut and spacer.
  4. Add Outer and secure with 2 x M3 Washers and 2 M3 Nuts.
  5. Remove the existing spool holder and, using the same self-tapping screws, attach the Fixing Plate in the indentation.
  6. Insert 4 x M3 25mm Hex Head Screws into the already affixed Outer and slide 2 x Roller Scate Bearings onto the spindles.
  7. Slide 2 x Roller Scate Bearings onto the spindles of an Inner and attach the Inner to the Outer using 4 x M3 Nuts.
  8. Insert 4 x M3 25mm Hex Head Screws into the remaining Outer and slide 2 x Roller Scate Bearings onto the spindles.
  9. Slide 2 x Roller Scate Bearings onto the spindles of the remaining Inner and attach the Inner to the Outer using 4 x M3 Nuts.
  10. Attach this assembly (steps 7 & 8) to the Slider using 2 x M3 x 12mm Hex Head Screws, 2 x M3 Washers and 2 x M3 Nuts.
  11. Remove the Butterfly Nut and place the Slider over the Fixing Plate and attach using the Butterfly Nut. Adjust for the reel you are printing with. Note that the Slider can be fixed facing in either direction according to reel width.

description.text:
InkOwl sells a large-capacity refillable ink cartridge system for the HP OfficeJet 8000 (and other printers using the 940 series cartridges). However, the cartridges need to stick out of the cartridge slots, requiring that the door that normally covers the cartridges be left open. HP tracks the state of the door with a switch at the upper right corner of the ink cartridge bay that is depressed by a flange on the door, and the printer will not operate if the door is open -- or, more accurately, if this switch is not depressed.

The instructions that come with the InkOwl cartridges suggest using a folded piece of cardboard to keep this switch pressed. This object is a substitute for the folded cardboard. It is designed with a flange for easy handling; you hold the piece with the flange to the left, slide it to the top right corner of the cartridge bay (if you look in that corner, you'll see a rectangular box with the switch traveller in the middle) and press it in until it fits firmly against the walls of the box (the piece is tapered for a snug fit). This keeps the switch depressed, making the printer think that the door is closed.

I prefere thumbtacks. At first i cover it's head with a little solder. The melting of the solder takes away a lot of the heat, when you solder the wires to it later.

Thumbtacks give a solid soldering connection and ... they are fairly cheap. All circuits schould be build with secure voltages. There is a part, you can print to put a 9V-Battery in. title: E3D/BLTOUCH Mount for FolgerTech Stock Extruder on an FT5.

description.text:
I got an E3D Lite hot end for my Folger Tech FT-5 and needed a holder for both it and my BLTOUCH. After several iterations, I arrived at a mount that puts the input of the E3D directly up against the output hole of the stock FolgerTech MK9 extruder with the pressure lever on the left. That is how my Folger Tech Ft-5 is arranged. My FT 2020 i3 has the lever on the right. I have not tried this on that machine but I would imagine that a mirror image could work.

I made it from ESUN PLA+ since there is no heat in that area.

comments.text:
I printed this out, without supports in PETG at .16 layer height with a .2mm nozzle. (My .4 is clogged but good, so I just kept using this one)
Anyhow, works great. I sanded the back edge just to line up the filament hole a little better. I also drilled a little out of the bottom of my stock Folgertech Aluminum i3 2020's extruder so I could get the PTFE tube right up next to the bearing and gear, the hard part being making a recess for the PTFE retention clip while keeping it all tight and square. Mission accomplished, filament goes through slick as silk!
Thanks!
